For months now, I’ve been sitting on one of the best cookbooks I’ve ever read - a book about bagels (one of my favorite foods) by a bagel guru named @cathybarrow. I’ve read it several times now, but felt intimidated by the process and never really made the time. Last night, I got some sad news about a special little boy and knew I wouldn’t be able to sleep. So instead, I got out the ingredients for bagels and began. Baking is soothing for me - I have to shut down my mind and focus, or else things will go wrong. I put the bagels in the fridge to proof and went to bed with a heavy heart but clearer mind. This morning came part two - and the calming ritual of it all did wonders to calm me. Plus - they were SO GOOD. Almost criminally good. The kids agreed, which makes it a true win. So, Cathy— I don’t know you, but I’m already a big fan. I can’t wait to bake my way through your book! #bagels #baking

Jalapeño cheddar bread: make it once, and you’ll make it weekly. Fan favorite over here.

3 cups (450g) flour (I use bread flour, but you can use all purpose)
2 tsp instant yeast 
2 tsp kosher salt 
1.5 c very warm water 
1/2 cup cheddar cheese
Your heart’s desired amount of jalapeños 

1.) mix everything in a large bowl
2.) cover with Saran wrap or a dish towel and set in a warm place for 2-3 hours, or until it’s doubled in size 
3.) place in the refrigerator overnight 
4.) remove the dough and let warm while you preheat your oven (with covered Dutch oven inside) to 450
5.) chop or grate your cheese
6.) use a scraper to fold in the cheese and jalapeños (JUST FOLD IT IN!)
7.) place seam side down on parchment paper and score the top
8.) place in the Dutch oven and let bake, covered for 30 mins
9.) remove the cover and bake for another 12-14 mins, or until golden
10.) let cool as long as your growling stomach will allow and enjoy!

What’s the secret to saving money when it comes to home decorating?

In my experience, it’s patience.

Sure, I’d *love* to have everything picture perfect the day I move in, but for me, that’s not an option. 

Instead, I try to intentionally collect things that I love — and that fit my budget. This means frequent trips to Goodwill, Dirt Cheap, and my one true love: Facebook Marketplace. 

I often leave these stores empty handed, but sometimes, I score big! And when I do… it’s like Christmas morning 🤣

Alas, my sad IKEA fiddle fig swooped in to save the day. Could it be that this was the best plan all along? Maybe. Do I still need to find a big, beautiful planter for my tree? Yes. Back to the drawing board.

Today is the last day of Heart Month. It’s also Rare Disease Day. CHD is not rare (1 in 110) but Maeve is rare — CHD plus several “rare diseases” makes her our miracle girl.

The reality is, though - for families like ours, every month is heart month. Ever day is rare disease day. 

I’ve been a little quiet this month because, as she gets older, it just gets harder to be warm and fuzzy about it all. It’s very rarely smiling faces clad in happy heart gear. It’s more often sad and overwhelming and increasingly difficult to navigate. 

The smiling girl in this photo has endured more trauma in the last 5 years than should be allowed.

CHD and rare diseases have taken so much from our family, and yet…

It’s also given us some of our dearest, most treasured friends. It’s realigned our values and priorities in a way that only a radical diagnosis could. It’s given us the clarity bask in the moments — big and small — that our family shares. 

I will never know or understand why this path was chosen for my child, but I pray that she knows that she is fearfully and wonderfully made; that her life has been mercifully maintained by the Lord so surely that her purpose here is great; and that her daddy, doctors and I will fight forever for her health and happiness. 

CHD sucks. But to quote our family motto, “Life is Hard, but God is Good.” #heartmonth

My kids woke up groggy just like theirs did. They argued about brushing their teeth and left half-eaten cereal on the counter. 

The night before, they read together and bickered a little and shared kisses and "I love yous" and goodnights.

They probably sang in the car on the way to school, just like mine did. 

Their parents received an earth-shattering phone call. I saw it on my newsfeed. The 13th school shooting this year— and it’s not even April.

It's long past time for change. Loving our neighbors as ourselves wasn't a suggestion. Neither was protecting the least of these. Kids can't write new laws, but we can.

Text READY to 644-33 if you're ready to do something about it.

Looking for a fun, screenless activity this summer? Try a secret book safe!
We picked up $1 books from Goodwill, covered the jackets with plastic bags, and painted the majority of the spines with puzzle glue.
Once it dried, we traced and cut out a hole with a box cutter, and painted the insides again with puzzle glue.
My kids filled their dried books with treasures to hide on their bookshelves.

I don’t know about you, but my kids’ shoes go from beautiful to looking like they’ve been playing in a swamp within 3 business days.

When they’re looking especially disgusting, this is my go-to:

-spray with Dawn Power Wash
-soak in HOT water with powdered Tide, Borax, and Oxiclean
-rinse well
-scrub (I have an electric scrubber that I use for this part, but a toothbrush with some elbow grease is just as effective!)
-rinse again
-cover with toilet paper so the gunk has a place to go
-sit out in the sun until they dry

Voila! Clean Nikes.

2 months after we started… the stairway gallery wall is done! 🙃🍾🥂 

Really and truly, I think the hardest part about hanging a gallery wall is making yourself do it. It can be so daunting and overwhelming. We did one wall in a day, and the second wall in another (granted, there were 2 months between those days 🤣) 

This art is a mix of hand-me-downs, Goodwill finds, reframed prints, and— my favorite addition— my dad’s old fireman helmet 👨🏻‍🚒

I had a lot of questions about how to use thrifted frames for new art, and I’ll post that reel next.

So… what do you think? Worth the hassle? Let me know!

My secret for affordable art? Goodwill frames!

This botanic print isn’t my style, but the gold frame definitely is. I used my tried and true method to frame this @teilart print and I couldn’t be happier with how it turned out. 

Next time you’re thrifting, don’t pay attention to *just* the art— keep an eye out for those frames. It can give you a beautiful, custom look for a fraction of the price. (Just be careful with those nails… they really will get you 🤣)

When we renovated our home, we were *sure* we’d use the side door as our main entrance. So, we put our mud room by the side door.

Turns out, we’ve never once used the side door. 💀 The front door is our go-to, which means our kids’ belongings are strewn across the house as they make their way to the mud room. 

Enter: creepy closet under the stairs.

I added subfloor and float floor, painted, installed a cubby system from Target (flipped on its side), and anchored 1x3 boards into the studs so that my kids won’t pull the hooks out of the wall 🙃

All in all, we spent under $125 (we already had the flooring) and I couldn’t be happier with how it turned out. What do you think?

Hi! 👋🏻There are some new folks around here (welcome!), so I thought I’d properly introduce myself.

I’m Eliza Morrill (pronounced like “moral” of the story) and I live in Georgia with my husband, Mike, our four wild kids, and our always-snoring bulldog, Bowie. 

We bought our 1873 Victorian home in 2019 and spent 3 (hellacious) years restoring it. Seriously. It was awful. But, somehow... worth it.

I’m a firm believer in the idea that a house is never “done”— there are always tweaks to be made and projects to be completed. That’s what makes it fun, ya know?

My dad recently bought a similar home right down the street from us, and though I thought I’d never, ever touch another historic project… it’s different when it’s not your own, and I am WILDLY excited about it.

So, welcome! Whether you’ve been here 8 years or 8 minutes, I’m honored that you’d choose to have my face in your feed.

There really is no place like home - especially for the holidays ✨

Maeve was discharged from the hospital on Friday, and we spent the day yesterday getting the house decorated for Christmas. We celebrated our Thanksgiving today, and I’m having my knee replaced on Tuesday. Never a dull moment, eh!? 😵‍💫🫠

But really, nothing makes me happier than having all of my people at home together - and the Christmas decorations that surround us are a big added bonus.

After so many holidays apart, having everyone together on the sofa (including Bowie!) is something I’ll never take for granted. 🤍

I’m two days post-knee replacement, and the sofa bed in the playroom is my new home. 

If you know me, you know that I am never not moving or tinkering or crossing something off of my to-do list, so this whole “mostly bed bound” thing is not really my speed.

But— this new, slow pace is probably just what I needed (as much as I hate to admit it.)

This Sunday marks the start of Advent, and this isn’t the first time I’ll have been forced to slow down and wait. Preparing my heart for Christmas— not just my home and kids’ calendars.

I’ve done all the decorating I can do. The hustling and bustling and last-minute Target runs won’t be in the cards this year, and I kind of love it. 

I just have to let the Christmas season *be*, and be okay with that. 

And, with a view like this (and my babies snoozing in their beds above me), it’s hard not to be.

Christmas is a week away. (Does that make your  stomach clench?)

There’s a big part of me that wants to spin into overdrive and run over the mental to-do list that is mostly— well— ✨not done.✨

I still have gifts to buy, and menus to plan, and — didn’t we do, like, a lot more activities last year? On and on and on. I feel the pressure to make Christmas as magical as possible, without spoiling my kids, while also making sure that we keep in mind the true meaning of Christmas.

THIS IS A LOT OF PRESSURE, YALL. 

But the reality is this: my kids don’t care if we have a meal that takes 4 hours or 4 minutes on Christmas Eve. They didn’t notice that I never got around to putting out all of the decorations this year. Honestly, I could probably wrap their gifts in toilet paper and I doubt they’d care (easier to rip into!)

The majority of the things on my list are only on it because I fool myself into thinking that they matter. 

When, really, the only thing that matters is that we are together, we are safe, and a Savior is on the way. 🤍
